To go down into oneself as into a dark mine or cavern is an expressive phrase. Aesop's story of the two wallets is referred to among many other writers by Horace, S. ii. 3. 299: “ Respicere ignoto discet pendentia tergo‚’' where see note. Jahn says this is due to the ignorance of the middle ages, and that in inscriptions the name Vettidius is often found, but Vec- tidius never. That does not decide the ease against the MSS„ which are for the most part in favour of Vectidii.

‘Cures' is the Sabine town in which tradition said Numa was born. The cir- cumstance of Vectidius being a Sabine might account for his thriftiness, for which those people were proverbial.
